explanation:
To determine compliance with the MISRA rule for well-formed for loops you must inspect any code that could contain for statements or influence loop control variables used in those for statements. The following symbols are required and why:

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: Direct callee from OS_BinSemGive; its implementation must be inspected for any for statements (and their three clauses) because called functions’ behavior is considered part of a for loop body.
- OS_BinSemGive_Impl: Direct callee from OS_BinSemGive; its body must be checked for for statements and for any modifications of potential loop counters/flags.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit: Callee of OS_ObjectIdGetById; included because for-loops in transitive callees are relevant when verifying loop-body behavior and side-effects.
- OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex: Callee of OS_ObjectIdGetById; included to check for for-loops or use of objects that could be used as loop counters or modified by loops.
- OS_ObjectIdConvertToken: Callee of OS_ObjectIdGetById; included for the same reason — its implementation could contain loops or modify objects that loop clauses use.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: Callee of OS_ObjectIdGetById; included to capture any loop-relevant behavior in that code path.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Callee of OS_BinSemGive_Impl; needs inspection for loops or modifications of shared objects that could act as loop counters/flags.
- OS_Posix_BinSemAcquireMutex: Callee of OS_BinSemGive_Impl; included because it may contain loops or side-effecting operations relevant to loop-well-formedness.

Additionally the following types/constants/macros referenced in OS_BinSemGive must be known so that any expressions used as loop counters or in loop clauses (in this function or in callees) can be understood and verified:

- OS_object_token_t: type of token argument passed to callees; needed to see whether objects of this type are used/modified by loops or used as loop counters/flags.
- osal_id_t: type of sem_id; needed to determine if this identifier or derived objects are used in loop clauses.
- int32: return type alias; included for completeness when examining expressions/assignments that could be loop counters or modified in loops.
- OS_SUCCESS: symbolic return code tested by OS_BinSemGive; needed to follow control flow (which branches lead to callees) when searching for loops reachable from this function.
- OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE: macro/constant passed to OS_ObjectIdGetById; needed to resolve overloads/conditional behavior inside OS_ObjectIdGetById that may introduce loops.
- LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: macro/constant passed to OS_ObjectIdGetById; likewise needed to understand control flow inside the callee(s).

Notes:
- Only the symbols that are directly or transitively invoked by OS_BinSemGive are listed because the MISRA rule requires considering the behavior of functions called within the for statement body. Even though OS_BinSemGive contains no for statement itself, its callees (and their callees) must be inspected to ensure no for-loop inlined/embedded in contexts that would make OS_BinSemGive violate the rule.
- Unit-test harness stubs (UT_*) seen in the static graph were not included because they are typically test instrumentation; include them only if your build/link setup actually inserts those calls into the production control flow of OS_BinSemGive. If present in the compiled function body, they should also be inspected for for-statements and side effects.
